---
title: "Pipeline Calculus for Lateralus"
author: bad-antics
date: 2026-04-05
abstract: We formalize the Lateralus pipeline operator as a category-theoretic composition. Our approach provides a unified semantics and optimizes performance.

---

# Introduction

The Lateralus language's pipeline operator is a fundamental construct in its design. While intuitive, its behavior is not immediately apparent from its syntax. In this paper, we provide a formal treatment of the pipeline operator using category theory.

## Section 1: Pipe Semantics

We define the pipe semantics as follows:
fn (x: int) -> (y: int) => int {
    let z = x + y
    return z
}
This definition captures the essence of the pipe operator: taking two input values and producing an output value by applying some function to them.

## Section 2: Associativity

To show associativity, consider three inputs `x`, `y`, and `z`. We can compose the pipe operators as follows:
fn (x: int) -> (y: int) => int; // fn1
fn (y: int) -> (z: int) => int; // fn2
fn (x: int, y: int, z: int) => int => int;

fn (x: int) -> (y: int => int) => (int => int); // fn3
fn (y: int) -> (z: int => int) => (int => int); // fn4
fn (int => int) => (int => int); // fn5
By composition, we get:
fn (x: int) -> (y: int => int) => (int => int);
This shows that the pipe operator is associative, allowing us to chain multiple compositions together.

## Section 3: Identity

The identity element for the pipe operator is trivially defined:
fn (x: int) -> (y: int) => x;
This identity element serves as a left or right unit in our category theory framework.

